{"title_page": "Agony (1992 video game)", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=October 2017}}\n{{Infobox video game\n|title = Agony\n|image = Agony Coverart.jpg\n|caption = Cover art by [[Roger Dean (artist)|Roger Dean]]\n|developer = Art & Magic\n|publisher = [[Psygnosis]]\n|designer = Yves Grolet\n|released = {{vgrelease|EU|1992}}\n|genre = [[Scrolling shooter]]\n|modes = [[Single-player video game|Single-player]]\n|platforms = [[Amiga]]\n}}\n\n'''''Agony''''' is a [[scrolling shooter|horizontally scrolling shooter]] with a surreal fantasy background. It was released by [[Psygnosis]] in 1992 for the [[Amiga]].<ref name=\"lemon\">{{cite web |title=Agony |url=http://www.lemonamiga.com/?game_id=40 |website=Lemon Amiga}}</ref> ''Agony'' features a barn owl flying its way through six worlds filled with monsters. The owl uses various waves of echolocation which the player fires at the enemies.\n\n==Plot==\nAccording to the manual backstory, the sun-wizard master Acanthropsis discovers the \"Cosmic Power\" with a toll on his life. Before dying he teaches it to his disciples, Alestes and Mentor. Alestes has been transformed into a barn owl, and has to pass through Mentor's traps and monsters in order to reach the Cosmic Power.\n\n==Development==\n{{Original research|section|date=April 2020}}\n\nThe game makes great use of many Amiga features such as scales of colors done with raster lines, [[halfbrite]] graphics mode for the between-level pictures, three layers of parallax scrolling using dual-playfield mode, in-game palette swapping and continuous flashing of the background palette to simulate additional colors. Featuring three floppies, the game ran on all Amiga computers. In common with other Amiga titles, the music was created with [[sampling (music)|sampled sounds]].\n\n==Music==\nThe theme song is by [[Tim Wright (Welsh musician)|Tim Wright]], a classically themed, piano-led instrumental. The title song was adapted without giving him proper credit by the keyboardist of [[Dimmu Borgir]] in the song \"Sorgens Kammer\" for their ''[[Stormbl\u00e5st]]'' album.<ref name=\"without credit\">[http://www.psygnosis.org/games/agony/files/notes.txt ''Agony'' notes at Psygnosiss]</ref> The band did not know about this. Following several months of communication between Wright and Dimmu Borgir, and in a nod to the composer, the band did not include the track on a later re-recording of ''Stormbl\u00e5st''.<ref name=\"re-recording\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20071203213746/http://www.punktv.ca/?c=104&a=1612 Re-recording information at Punk TV]</ref> The title song is also slightly different from the version that Wright originally submitted to Art & Magic. Franck Sauer advised Wright that he could source improved piano sounds for the piece, and requested permission to change them. Wright agreed, but did not hear the end result before the game went to the final master, and consequently some notes within the piece were transposed; this 'mistake' was also covered by [[Dimmu Borgir]].<ref name=\"without credit\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://francksauer.com/index.php/games/test/15-games/published-games/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=10:agony&catid=15:published-games ''Agony''] page from the game's artist Franck Sauer\n* [http://hol.abime.net/?id=3209 ''Agony''] at Amiga Hall of Light\n* [http://www.psygnosis.org/games/agony ''Agony''] at Psygnosis.org\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Agony (Video Game)}}\n[[Category:1992 video games]]\n[[Category:Amiga games]]\n[[Category:Amiga-only games]]\n[[Category:Europe-exclusive video games]]\n[[Category:Psygnosis games]]\n[[Category:Horizontally scrolling shooters]]\n[[Category:Video games scored by Jeroen Tel]]\n[[Category:Video games scored by Tim Wright]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in Belgium]]\n[[Category:Fantasy video games]]\n[[Category:Single-player video games]]\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=October 2017}}\n{{Infobox video game\n|title = Agony\n|image = Agony Coverart.jpg\n|caption = Cover art by [[Roger Dean (artist)|Roger Dean]]\n|developer = Art & Magic\n|publisher = [[Psygnosis]]\n|designer = Yves Grolet\n|released = {{vgrelease|EU|1992}}\n|genre = [[Scrolling shooter]]\n|modes = [[Single-player video game|Single-player]]\n|platforms = [[Amiga]]\n}}\n\n'''''Agony''''' is a [[scrolling shooter|horizontally-scrolling shooter]] with a surreal fantasy background. It was released by [[Psygnosis]] in 1992 for the [[Amiga]].<ref name=\"lemon\">{{cite web |title=Agony |url=http://www.lemonamiga.com/?game_id=40 |website=Lemon Amiga}}</ref> ''Agony'' features a barn owl flying its way through six worlds filled with monsters. The owl uses various waves of echolocation which the player fires at the enemies.\n\n==Plot==\nAccording to the manual backstory, the sun-wizard master Acanthropsis discovers the \"Cosmic Power\" with a toll on his life. Before dying he teaches it to his disciples, Alestes and Mentor. Alestes has been transformed into a barn owl, and has to pass through Mentor's traps and monsters in order to reach the Cosmic Power.\n\n==Development==\n{{Original research|section|date=April 2020}}\n\nThe game makes great use of many Amiga features such as scales of colors done with raster lines, [[halfbrite]] graphics mode for the between-level pictures, three layers of parallax scrolling using dual-playfield mode, in-game palette swapping and continuous flashing of the background palette to simulate additional colors. Featuring three floppies, the game ran on all Amiga computers. In common with other Amiga titles, the music was created with [[sampling (music)|sampled sounds]].\n\n==Music==\nThe theme song is by [[Tim Wright (Welsh musician)|Tim Wright]], a classically themed, piano-led instrumental. The title song was adapted without giving him proper credit by the keyboardist of [[Dimmu Borgir]] in the song \"Sorgens Kammer\" for their ''[[Stormbl\u00e5st]]'' album.<ref name=\"without credit\">[http://www.psygnosis.org/games/agony/files/notes.txt ''Agony'' notes at Psygnosiss]</ref> The band did not know about this. Following several months of communication between Wright and Dimmu Borgir, and in a nod to the composer, the band did not include the track on a later re-recording of ''Stormbl\u00e5st''.<ref name=\"re-recording\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20071203213746/http://www.punktv.ca/?c=104&a=1612 Re-recording information at Punk TV]</ref> The title song is also slightly different from the version that Wright originally submitted to Art & Magic. Franck Sauer advised Wright that he could source improved piano sounds for the piece, and requested permission to change them. Wright agreed, but did not hear the end result before the game went to the final master, and consequently some notes within the piece were transposed; this 'mistake' was also covered by [[Dimmu Borgir]].<ref name=\"without credit\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://francksauer.com/index.php/games/test/15-games/published-games/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=10:agony&catid=15:published-games ''Agony''] page from the game's artist Franck Sauer\n* [http://hol.abime.net/?id=3209 ''Agony''] at Amiga Hall of Light\n* [http://www.psygnosis.org/games/agony ''Agony''] at Psygnosis.org\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Agony (Video Game)}}\n[[Category:1992 video games]]\n[[Category:Amiga games]]\n[[Category:Amiga-only games]]\n[[Category:Europe-exclusive video games]]\n[[Category:Psygnosis games]]\n[[Category:Horizontally scrolling shooters]]\n[[Category:Video games scored by Jeroen Tel]]\n[[Category:Video games scored by Tim Wright]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in Belgium]]\n[[Category:Fantasy video games]]\n[[Category:Single-player video games]]\n", "name_user": "Dgpop", "label": "safe", "comment": "removed dash", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Agony_(1992_video_game)"}
